		if classSize >= size 'fits'
			// A raw OS thread (id < 0) reaches the shared raw mcache shard. Two cases:
			//   (a) PRE-SCHEDULER main (no `async` yet → `__slab_proc_at(0) == 0`): the
			//       lone thread, so its pop is single-writer — lockless, no overhead on
			//       ordinary non-async programs.
			//   (b) a genuine raw thread WHILE a scheduler runs (subprocess sync worker
			//       / IOCP poller — main is then P[0], id 0): it shares the raw shard
			//       with the OTHER raw threads, so the pop is NOT single-writer.
			//       Serialize the whole class-alloc under __slab_lock; the inner refill
			//       re-acquires it, which is safe because __slab_lock is a recursive
			//       Windows CRITICAL_SECTION. `__gt_init` runs on main before any worker
			//       exists, so no raw thread ever takes the unlocked (a) path.
