	// whose alloc side is serialized under __slab_lock once a scheduler runs (see
	// __slab_alloc). Once a scheduler is up (`__slab_proc_at(0) != 0`), ANY free of
	// such a slot — by the owning raw thread, another raw thread, or a real P that
	// received the slot through cross-thread data sharing — MUST take the same lock,
	// or it races the raw thread's allocation pop / another raw free. (The
	// `owningP == myId` raw==raw==-1 case and the real-P `__slab_proc_at(<0)==0`
	// fallback-local case both reach an UNLOCKED push otherwise.) The recursive
	// CRITICAL_SECTION makes the inner mcentral-return re-acquire safe. Before the
	// scheduler exists the lone main thread is the only writer → lockless.
